 {"id":"jeffreysprompts.com-bnc3","title":"Add keyboard alternatives for mobile swipe actions","description":"# Task: Add Keyboard Alternatives for Swipe Actions

## Context
SwipeablePromptCard has powerful touch gestures (swipe left/right, long-press, double-tap) that are completely inaccessible to keyboard users. While these are mobile-optimized, keyboard users on desktop need equivalent access.

## Current Mobile-Only Actions
1. **Swipe left**: Copy prompt to clipboard
2. **Swipe right**: Add to basket
3. **Double-tap**: Save/favorite
4. **Long-press**: Open quick actions menu

## Desktop Already Has
- Copy button on PromptCard ✓
- View button opens modal with all actions ✓

## Missing Keyboard Equivalents
The PromptCard (desktop) is missing:
1. **Add to basket** button (only available via swipe or modal)
2. **Save/favorite** functionality (not implemented on desktop)

## Proposed Solution

### Option A: Add Basket Button to PromptCard Footer (Recommended)
```tsx
// PromptCard.tsx - Add basket button next to Copy
<div className="flex items-center gap-2">
  <Button
    size="sm"
    variant="ghost"
    className="h-8 px-2"
    onClick={handleAddToBasket}
    disabled={isInBasket}
    aria-label={isInBasket ? "Already in basket" : "Add to basket"}
  >
    {isInBasket ? (
      <Check className="w-4 h-4 text-emerald-500" aria-hidden="true" />
    ) : (
      <ShoppingBasket className="w-4 h-4" aria-hidden="true" />
    )}
  </Button>

  {/* Existing Copy button */}
  <Button ... />

  {/* Existing View button */}
  <Button ... />
</div>
```

### Option B: Keyboard Shortcut on Card Focus
Add keyboard shortcuts when card is focused:
```tsx
const handleKeyDown = useCallback((e: React.KeyboardEvent) => {
  switch (e.key) {
    case 'c':
      if (e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey) {
        e.preventDefault();
        handleCopy();
      }
      break;
    case 'b':
      if (e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey) {
        e.preventDefault();
        handleAddToBasket();
      }
      break;
  }
}, [handleCopy, handleAddToBasket]);

<Card 
  tabIndex={0} 
  onKeyDown={handleKeyDown}
  role="article"
  aria-label={prompt.title}
>
```

### Option C: Context Menu on Right-Click
```tsx
const handleContextMenu = useCallback((e: React.MouseEvent) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  // Show custom context menu with Copy, Add to Basket, etc.
}, []);

<Card onContextMenu={handleContextMenu}>
```

## Recommended Approach
**Option A** is simplest and most discoverable:
- Visual button = no learning curve
- Keyboard accessible by default (Tab + Enter)
- Consistent with existing UI pattern

**Consider also adding Option B** for power users who want speed.

## Implementation for Option A

### 1. Add basket hook to PromptCard
```tsx
import { useBasket } from "@/hooks/use-basket";

export function PromptCard({ prompt, ... }) {
  const { addItem, isInBasket } = useBasket();
  const inBasket = isInBasket(prompt.id);

  const handleAddToBasket = useCallback((e: MouseEvent) => {
    e.stopPropagation();
    if (!inBasket) {
      addItem(prompt.id);
      success("Added to basket", prompt.title);
    }
  }, [prompt, inBasket, addItem, success]);

  // ... render basket button in footer
}
```

### 2. Update button group layout
Current: Copy | View
New: Basket | Copy | View

May need to adjust button sizes or use icon-only for all three:
```tsx
<div className="flex items-center gap-1">
  <Button size="sm" variant="ghost" className="h-8 w-8 p-0" ...>
    <ShoppingBasket className="w-4 h-4" />
  </Button>
  <Button size="sm" variant="ghost" className="h-8 w-8 p-0" ...>
    <Copy className="w-4 h-4" />
  </Button>
  <Button size="sm" className="h-8 px-3" ...>
    View
    <ChevronRight className="w-4 h-4 ml-1" />
  </Button>
</div>
```

## Testing
1. Tab to PromptCard - focus visible
2. Tab through buttons - all accessible
3. Enter on basket button - adds to basket
4. Enter on basket button again - shows "already in basket" state
5. Verify with screen reader

